reasoning: I’m going to be upfront: I don’t have the data I need to make a conviction either way, and Alphabet (GOOG) falls outside my usual circle of competence. 1. Circle of Competence: I’ve spent my life understanding businesses like Coca-Cola, See’s Candies and simple insurance operations, not complex online advertising platforms and search algorithms. If I don’t understand the engine under the hood, I’m better off sitting on my hands. 2. Competitive Moat: On paper Google has network effects and scale in search and digital ads, but I can’t assess from zero data how sustainable that advantage will be amid regulatory pressures and fast-moving ad tech competitors. 3. Management Quality: Sundar Pichai and the team have guided Google well, yet without detailed insights I can’t judge whether they’ll allocate capital in shareholders’ best interest over the next 20 years. 4. Financial Health and Consistency: I’ve got no fundamentals to review—no revenue growth rates, profit margins or debt levels—so I simply can’t evaluate consistency of earnings or strength of the balance sheet. 5. Valuation vs. Intrinsic Value: With no intrinsic-value model available, I can’t tell if the current price leaves me a margin of safety. 6. Long-Term Prospects: The internet economy likely has legs, but the pace of change and regulatory risk is high. 7. Comparison to Current Opportunities: I’d rather deploy capital into businesses with clear, proven economics and durable moats that I understand. In short, I don’t know enough, so I’ll pass for now and keep looking for opportunities where my edge is real.
